[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Prometheus originated at SoundCloud in 2012 and was accepted by the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) in 2016, graduating from incubation in 2018.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] It is commonly paired with Grafana for dashboard visualization and supports a wide range of exporters and integrations.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Prometheus was developed at SoundCloud starting in 2012, after the company found that its existing metrics tools, based on StatsD and Graphite, could not meet the demands of its containerized infrastructure.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] The design goals included a multi-dimensional data model, operational simplicity, scalable data collection, and a powerful query language in a single tool.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] The project was open source from the start and was adopted by Boxever and Docker users before any official announcement.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] The design was influenced by Borgmon, Google's internal time-series monitoring system, which treated time-series data as a source for alert generation.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] By 2013, Prometheus was in production use at SoundCloud.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] The project was publicly announced in January 2015.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] In May 2016, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation accepted Prometheus as its second incubated project, after Kubernetes.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] In August 2018, the CNCF announced that Prometheus had graduated from incubation.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Prometheus 1.0 was released in July 2016.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Subsequent releases through 2016 and 2017 led to Prometheus 2.0 in November 2017, which introduced a new storage engine with significantly improved performance and reduced disk usage.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] A typical Prometheus monitoring deployment consists of several components working together.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Exporters run on monitored hosts to collect and expose local metrics.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] The Prometheus server scrapes those exporters at a configured interval, aggregates the data, and stores it locally.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Alertmanager receives alerts from Prometheus and handles routing, grouping, and silencing before forwarding notifications.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Grafana is commonly used to build dashboards from Prometheus data.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Queries against all of these are written in PromQL, Prometheus's native query language.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Prometheus data is organized as named metrics, each optionally qualified by an arbitrary number of key-value label pairs.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Labels can identify the data source (server name, datacenter) or carry application-specific context such as HTTP status code, request method, or endpoint.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Querying in real time against any combination of labels is what makes the data model multi-dimensional.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Prometheus stores data locally on disk for fast writes and queries.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Metrics can also be forwarded to remote storage backends, including Grafana Mimir and other Prometheus-compatible systems.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Prometheus collects data through a pull model: the server periodically queries a configured list of targets (exporters) and aggregates the returned time-series values.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Prometheus includes several service discovery mechanisms to automatically locate targets in dynamic environments.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Prometheus provides its own query language, PromQL (Prometheus Query Language), which allows users to select and aggregate time-series data.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] The language includes time-oriented constructs such as the rate() function, instant vectors, and range vectors that return multiple samples per series over a specified time window.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Alert rules in Prometheus specify a condition and a duration; if the condition holds for that duration, Prometheus fires an alert to Alertmanager.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Alertmanager handles silencing, inhibition, and routing to notification destinations including email, Slack, and PagerDuty.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Additional targets such as Microsoft Teams can be reached through the Alertmanager webhook receiver interface.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Prometheus includes its own time series database.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Recent data (by default, one to three hours) is held in a combination of memory and mmap-backed files.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Older data is written to persistent blocks indexed with an inverted index, which suits Prometheus's label-based query patterns.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] A background compaction process merges smaller blocks into larger ones to reduce read overhead.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Durability against crashes is provided by a write-ahead log (WAL).
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Prometheus includes a basic expression browser but is not a full dashboard system.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Grafana is the standard pairing, querying Prometheus via PromQL to produce dashboards; the need to deploy and maintain Grafana separately is sometimes cited as an operational drawback.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Prometheus favors white-box monitoring, where applications publish internal metrics for collection.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Exporters and agents are available for many applications and systems.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] For transition from existing monitoring stacks, Prometheus supports several protocols: Graphite, StatsD, SNMP, JMX, and CollectD.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Metrics are typically retained for a few weeks.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] For longer retention, Prometheus can stream data to remote storage backends.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] An effort to standardize the Prometheus exposition format as OpenMetrics has gained adoption from several vendors, including InfluxData's TICK suite, InfluxDB, Google Cloud Platform, Datadog, and New Relic.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] The OpenMetrics specification is maintained separately from the Prometheus project.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] Prometheus client libraries are available for most major programming languages.
[src:victoriametrics/prometheus-software] The POCO C++ Libraries expose Prometheus metrics through the `Poco::Prometheus` namespace.
[src:victoriametrics/time-series-database] A **time series database** is a software system that is optimized for storing and serving time series through associated pairs of time(s) and value(s).
[src:victoriametrics/time-series-database] In some fields, *time series* may be called profiles, curves, traces or trends.
[src:victoriametrics/time-series-database] Several early time series databases are associated with industrial applications which could efficiently store measured values from sensory equipment (also referred to as data historians), but now are used in support of a much wider range of applications.
[src:victoriametrics/time-series-database] In many cases, the repositories of time-series data will utilize compression algorithms to manage the data efficiently.
[src:victoriametrics/time-series-database] Although it is possible to store time-series data in many different database types, the design of these systems with time as a key index is distinctly different from relational databases which reduce discrete relationships through referential models.
[src:victoriametrics/time-series-database] Time series datasets are relatively large and uniform compared to other datasets―usually being composed of a timestamp and associated data.
[src:victoriametrics/time-series-database] Time series datasets can also have fewer relationships between data entries in different tables and don't require indefinite storage of entries.
[src:victoriametrics/time-series-database] The unique properties of time series datasets mean that time series databases can provide significant improvements in storage space and performance over general purpose databases.
[src:victoriametrics/time-series-database] For instance, due to the uniformity of time series data, specialized compression algorithms can provide improvements over regular compression algorithms designed to work on less uniform data.
[src:victoriametrics/time-series-database] Time series databases can also be configured to regularly delete (or downsample) old data, unlike regular databases which are designed to store data indefinitely.
[src:victoriametrics/time-series-database] Special database indices can also provide boosts in query performance.
[src:victoriametrics/time-series-database] Time series databases are commonly designed for append-heavy workloads, where large numbers of measurements or events are continuously written together with timestamps.
[src:victoriametrics/time-series-database] Specialized time series management systems have been developed for data from monitoring, automation, the Internet of Things, and cyber-physical systems, where data may be produced at high velocity and in large volumes.
[src:victoriametrics/time-series-database] Common design goals include high-throughput data ingestion, low-latency queries over time ranges, efficient compression, and support for aggregation or downsampling over time windows.
[src:victoriametrics/time-series-database] Many systems also organize data by tags, devices, sensors, or other metadata, so that users can retrieve measurements by both time range and source.
[src:victoriametrics/time-series-database] Time series databases are used in application areas where data is collected continuously over time.
[src:victoriametrics/time-series-database] Examples include industrial monitoring, operational historians, infrastructure and application monitoring, Internet of Things sensor data, energy systems, financial market data, and scientific measurements.
[src:victoriametrics/time-series-database] In monitoring applications, time series database systems may need to process large amounts of sensor or metric data in real time, execute continuous queries, and support analytical tasks such as data exploration, anomaly detection, predictive modeling, trend analysis, and missing-value recovery.
[src:victoriametrics/time-series-database] Time series databases are often used as storage and query systems for downstream analytical tasks, including forecasting, anomaly detection, imputation, and pattern matching.
[src:victoriametrics/time-series-database] Some systems also integrate analytical or machine-learning functions closer to the database layer, allowing users to invoke forecasting or anomaly detection through database query interfaces such as SQL.
[src:victoriametrics/time-series-database] Recent research in time series analysis has also explored large pre-trained models for tasks such as forecasting, imputation, and anomaly detection.
[src:victoriametrics/time-series-database] These models are usually discussed as analytical methods for time series data rather than as defining features of time series databases.
[src:victoriametrics/time-series-database] The following database systems have functionality optimized for handling time series data.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Simply put, `metric` is a numeric measure or observation of something.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] To track how many requests our application serves, we’ll define a metric with the name `requests_total`.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] You can be more specific here by saying `requests_success_total` (for only successful requests) or `request_errors_total` (for requests which failed).
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Choosing a metric name is very important and supposed to clarify what is actually measured to every person who reads it, just like **variable names** in programming.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The meta-information - a set of `labels` in curly braces - gives us a context for which `path` and with what `code` the `request` was served.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Label-value pairs are always of a `string` type.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] VictoriaMetrics data model is schemaless, which means there is no need to define metric names or their labels in advance.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The user is free to add or change ingested metrics anytime.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Actually, the metric name is also a label with a special name `__name__`.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The `__name__` key could be omitted Available from v1.111.0 for simplicity.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Labels can be automatically attached to the time series written via vmagent or Prometheus .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] VictoriaMetrics supports enforcing of label filters for query API to emulate data isolation.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] However, the real data isolation can be achieved via multi-tenancy .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] A combination of a metric name and its labels defines a `time series`.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] For example, `requests_total{path="/", code="200"}` and `requests_total{path="/", code="403"}` are two different time series because they have different values for `code` label.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The number of unique time series has an impact on database resource usage.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] See what is an active time series and what is high churn rate docs for details.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The number of unique time series is named `cardinality`.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Too big number of unique time series is named `high cardinality`.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] High cardinality may result in increased resource usage at VictoriaMetrics.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Every unique time series may consist of an arbitrary number of `(value, timestamp)` data points (aka `raw samples`) sorted by `timestamp`.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] VictoriaMetrics stores all the `values` as float64 with extra compression applied.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] This allows storing precise integer values with up to 12 decimal digits and any floating-point values with up to 12 significant decimal digits.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] If the value has more than 12 significant decimal digits, then the less significant digits can be lost when storing them in VictoriaMetrics.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The `timestamp` is a Unix timestamp with millisecond precision.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Resolution is the minimum interval between raw samples of the time series .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Here we have a time series `requests_total{path="/health", code="200"}` which has a value update each `30s`.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] This means, its resolution is also a `30s`.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] In terms of pull model , resolution is equal to `scrape_interval` and is controlled by the monitoring system (server).
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] For push model , resolution is an interval between samples timestamps and is controlled by a client (metrics collector).
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Try to keep time series resolution consistent, since some MetricsQL functions may expect it to be so.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Internally, VictoriaMetrics does not have the notion of a metric type.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The concept of a metric type exists specifically to help users to understand how the metric was measured.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Counter is a metric, which counts some events.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Its value increases or stays the same over time.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] `counter reset`, when the metric resets to zero.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The `counter reset` can occur when the service, which exposes the counter, restarts.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] So, the `counter` metric shows the number of observed events since the service start.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] In programming, `counter` is a variable that you **increment** each time something happens.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] `vm_http_requests_total` is a typical example of a counter.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The interpretation of a graph above is that time series `vm_http_requests_total{instance="localhost:8428", job="victoriametrics", path="api/v1/query_range"}` was rapidly changing from 1:38 pm to 1:39 pm, then there were no changes until 1:41 pm.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Counter is used for measuring the number of events, like the number of requests, errors, logs, messages, etc.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] For example, `request_duration_seconds_sum` counter may sum the durations of all the requests.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Every duration may have a fractional value in seconds, e.g.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] So the cumulative sum of all the request durations may be fractional too.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] It is recommended to put `_total`, `_sum` or `_count` suffix to `counter` metric names, so such metrics can be easily differentiated by humans from other metric types.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The metric `process_resident_memory_anon_bytes` on the graph shows the memory usage of the application at every given time.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] It is changing frequently, going up and down showing how the process allocates and frees the memory.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] In programming, `gauge` is a variable to which you **set** a specific value as it changes.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The most common MetricsQL functions used with gauges are aggregation functions and rollup functions .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Histogram is a set of counter metrics with different `vmrange` or `le` labels.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The `vmrange` or `le` labels define measurement boundaries of a particular bucket.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] When the observed measurement hits a particular bucket, then the corresponding counter is incremented.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Histogram buckets usually have `_bucket` suffix in their names.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] For example, VictoriaMetrics tracks the distribution of rows processed per query with the `vm_rows_read_per_query` histogram.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The `vm_rows_read_per_query_bucket{vmrange="4.084e+02...4.642e+02"} 2` line means that there were 2 queries with the number of rows in the range `(408.4 - 464.2]` since the last VictoriaMetrics start.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The counters ending with `_bucket` suffix allow estimating arbitrary percentile for the observed measurement with the help of histogram_quantile function.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The `sum(...) by (vmrange)` calculates per-bucket events by summing per-instance buckets with the same `vmrange` values.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The `histogram_quantile(0.99, ...)` calculates 99th percentile over `vmrange` buckets returned at step 2.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] These counters allow calculating the average measurement value on a particular lookbehind window.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Grafana doesn’t understand buckets with `vmrange` labels, so the prometheus_buckets function must be used for converting buckets with `vmrange` labels to buckets with `le` labels before building heatmaps in Grafana.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Histograms are usually used for measuring the distribution of latency, sizes of elements (batch size, for example) etc.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] VictoriaMetrics histogram supported by VictoriaMetrics/metrics instrumentation library.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Victoriametrics histogram automatically handles bucket boundaries, so users don’t need to think about them.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Summary metric type is quite similar to histogram and is used for quantiles calculations.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Summaries are usually used for tracking the pre-defined percentiles for latency, sizes of elements (batch size, for example) etc.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] As was said at the beginning of the types of metrics section, metric type defines how it was measured.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] VictoriaMetrics TSDB doesn’t know about metric types.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] All it sees are metric names, labels, values, and timestamps.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] What are these metrics, what do they measure, and how - all this depends on the application which emits them.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] To instrument your application with metrics compatible with VictoriaMetrics we recommend using github.com/VictoriaMetrics/metrics package.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] See more details on how to use it in this article .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] VictoriaMetrics is also compatible with Prometheus client libraries for metrics instrumentation .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] We recommend following Prometheus naming convention for metrics .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] There are no strict restrictions, so any metric name and labels are accepted by VictoriaMetrics.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] But the convention helps to keep names meaningful, descriptive, and clear to other people.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Following convention is a good practice.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Every measurement can contain an arbitrary number of `key="value"` labels.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The good practice is to keep this number limited.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Otherwise, it would be difficult to deal with measurements containing a big number of labels.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] By default, VictoriaMetrics limits the number of labels per measurement to `40` and drops other labels.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] This limit can be changed via `-maxLabelsPerTimeseries` command-line flag if necessary (but this isn’t recommended).
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Every label value can contain an arbitrary string value.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The good practice is to use short and meaningful label values to describe the attribute of the metric, not to tell the story about it.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] For example, label-value pair `environment="prod"` is ok, but `log_message="long log message with a lot of details..."` is not ok.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] By default, VictoriaMetrics limits label’s value size with 4KiB.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] This limit can be changed via `-maxLabelValueLen` command-line flag.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] It is very important to keep under control the number of unique label values, since every unique label value leads to a new time series .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Try to avoid using volatile label values such as session ID or query ID in order to avoid excessive resource usage and database slowdown.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Cluster version of VictoriaMetrics supports multi-tenancy for data isolation.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Multi-tenancy can be emulated for single-server version of VictoriaMetrics by adding labels on write path and enforcing labels filtering on read path .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] VictoriaMetrics supports both models used in modern monitoring applications: push and pull .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The client (application) decides when and where to send its metrics.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] VictoriaMetrics supports many protocols for data ingestion (aka `push protocols`) - see the full list here .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] All the protocols are fully compatible with VictoriaMetrics data model and can be used in production.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] We recommend using the github.com/VictoriaMetrics/metrics package for pushing application metrics to VictoriaMetrics.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] It is also possible to use already existing clients compatible with the protocols listed above like Telegraf for InfluxDB line protocol .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] It is allowed to push/write metrics to single-node VictoriaMetrics , to cluster component vminsert and to vmagent .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] See Foiled by the Firewall: A Tale of Transition From Prometheus to VictoriaMetrics elaborating more on why Percona switched from pull to push model.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] In pull model, the monitoring system needs to be aware of all the applications it needs to monitor.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The metrics are scraped (pulled) from the known applications (aka `scrape targets`) via HTTP protocol on a regular basis (aka `scrape_interval`).
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] VictoriaMetrics supports discovering Prometheus-compatible targets and scraping metrics from them in the same way as Prometheus does - see these docs .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Metrics scraping is supported by single-node VictoriaMetrics and by vmagent .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] VictoriaMetrics supports both push and pull models for data collection.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Many installations use exclusively one of these models, or both at once.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] In this approach the additional component is used - vmagent .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Vmagent is a lightweight agent whose main purpose is to collect, filter, relabel and deliver metrics to VictoriaMetrics.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] It supports all push and pull protocols mentioned above.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The basic monitoring setup of VictoriaMetrics and vmagent is described in the example docker-compose manifest .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] In this example vmagent scrapes a list of targets and forwards collected data to VictoriaMetrics .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] VictoriaMetrics is then used as a datasource for Grafana installation for querying collected data.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] VictoriaMetrics components allow building more advanced topologies.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] VictoriaMetrics in this example may be either single-node VictoriaMetrics or VictoriaMetrics Cluster .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Vmagent also allows replicating the same data to multiple destinations .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] VictoriaMetrics provides an HTTP API for serving read queries.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The API is used in various integrations such as Grafana .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The same API is also used by VMUI - a graphical User Interface for querying and visualizing metrics.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The API consists of two main handlers for serving instant queries and range queries .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The result of Instant query is a list of time series matching the filter in `query` expression.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Each returned series contains exactly one `(timestamp, value)` entry, where `timestamp` equals to the `time` query arg, while the `value` contains `query` result at the requested `time`.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The data above contains a list of samples for the `foo_bar` time series with time intervals between samples ranging from 1m to 3m.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] In response, VictoriaMetrics returns a single sample-timestamp pair with a value of `3` for the series `foo_bar` at the given moment in time `2022-05-10T08:03:00Z`.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] But, if we take a look at the original data sample again, we’ll see that there is no raw sample at `2022-05-10T08:03:00Z`.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The time range in which VictoriaMetrics will try to locate a replacement for a missing data sample is equal to `5m` by default and can be overridden via the `step` parameter.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Instant queries can return multiple time series, but always only one data sample per series.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The result of Range query is a list of time series matching the filter in `query` expression.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Each returned series contains `(timestamp, value)` results for the `query` executed at `start`, `start+step`, `start+2*step`, …, `start+N*step` timestamps.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] In other words, Range query is an Instant query executed independently at `start`, `start+step`, …, `start+N*step` timestamps with the only difference that an instant query does not return `ephemeral` samples (see below).
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Instead, if the database does not contain any samples for the requested time and step, it simply returns an empty result.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] But, if we take a look at the original data sample again, we’ll see that it contains only 13 raw samples.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] What happens here is that the range query is actually an instant query executed `1 + (start-end)/step` times on the time range from `start` to `end`.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The blue dotted lines in the figure are the moments when the instant query was executed.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Since the instant query retains the ability to return replacements for missing points, the graph contains two types of data points: `real` and `ephemeral`.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] `ephemeral` data points always repeat the closest raw sample that occurred before (see red arrow on the pic above).
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] According to these specifics, the range query assumes that if there is a missing raw sample then it is likely a missed scrape, so it fills it with the previous raw sample.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The same will work for cases when `step` is lower than the actual interval between samples.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] In fact, if we set `step=1s` for the same request, we’ll get about 1 thousand data points in response, where most of them are `ephemeral`.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Sometimes, the lookbehind window for locating the datapoint isn’t big enough and the graph will contain a gap.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] For range queries, lookbehind window isn’t equal to the `step` parameter.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] It is calculated as the median of the intervals between the last 20 raw samples in the requested time range.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] In this way, VictoriaMetrics automatically adjusts the lookbehind window to fill gaps and detect stale series at the same time.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Range queries are mostly used for plotting time series data over specified time ranges.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] If you need to export raw samples from VictoriaMetrics, then take a look at export APIs .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] By default, Victoria Metrics does not immediately return the recently written samples.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Instead, it retrieves the last results written prior to the time specified by the `-search.latencyOffset` command-line flag, which has a default offset of 30 seconds.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] This is true for both `query` and `query_range` and may give the impression that data is written to the VM with a 30-second delay.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] This flag prevents from non-consistent results due to the fact that only part of the values are scraped in the last scrape interval.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] It can be overridden on per-query basis via `latency_offset` query arg.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] VictoriaMetrics buffers recently ingested samples in memory for up to a few seconds and then periodically flushes these samples to disk.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] This buffering improves data ingestion performance.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The buffered samples are invisible in query results, even if `-search.latencyOffset` command-line flag is set to 0, or if `latency_offset` query arg is set to 0.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] You can send GET request to `/internal/force_flush` http handler at single-node VictoriaMetrics or to `vmstorage` at cluster version of VictoriaMetrics in order to forcibly flush the buffered samples to disk, so they become visible for querying.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The `/internal/force_flush` handler is provided for debugging and testing purposes only.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Do not call it in production, since this may significantly slow down data ingestion performance and increase resource usage.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] VictoriaMetrics provide a special query language for executing read queries - MetricsQL .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] It is a PromQL -like query language with a powerful set of functions and features for working specifically with time series data.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] MetricsQL is backward-compatible with PromQL, so it shares most of the query concepts.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The basic concepts for PromQL and MetricsQL are described here .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] In sections instant query and range query we’ve already used MetricsQL to get data for metric `foo_bar`.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] A single metric name may correspond to multiple time series with distinct label sets.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The query above returns all time series with the name `requests_total` and label `code="200"`.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] We use the operator `=` to match label value.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The query above returns all time series with `requests_total` name, which simultaneously have labels `code="200"` and `path="/home"`.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Sometimes it is required to return all the time series for multiple metric names.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] As was mentioned in the data model section , the metric name is just an ordinary label with a special name - `__name__`.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The query above returns series for two metrics: `requests_error_total` and `requests_success_total`.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] MetricsQL supports selecting time series, which match at least one of multiple “or” filters.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Such filters must be delimited by `or` inside curly braces.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The number of `or` groups can be arbitrary.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The number of `,`-delimited label filters per each `or` group can be arbitrary.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Per-group filters are applied with `and` operation, e.g. they select series simultaneously matching all the filters in the group.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] If you need to select series matching multiple filters for the same label, then it is better from performance PoV to use regexp filter `{label=~"value1|...|valueN"}` instead of `{label="value1" or ... or label="valueN"}`.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] This allows performing various calculations across multiple metrics.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Combining multiple time series with arithmetic operations requires an understanding of matching rules.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Otherwise, the query may break or may lead to incorrect results.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] These operators may be applied to arbitrary MetricsQL expressions as with arithmetic operators.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The result of the comparison operation is time series with only matching data points.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] MetricsQL allows aggregating and grouping of time series.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Time series are grouped by the given set of labels and then the given aggregation function is applied individually per each group.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] See docs for aggregate functions in MetricsQL .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] One of the most widely used functions for counters is rate .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] It calculates the average per-second increase rate individually per each matching time series.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] By default, VictoriaMetrics calculates the `rate` over raw samples on the lookbehind window specified in the `step` param passed either to instant query or to range query .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] In this case VictoriaMetrics uses the specified lookbehind window - `5m` (5 minutes) - for calculating the average per-second increase rate.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Bigger lookbehind windows usually lead to smoother graphs.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] `rate` strips metric name while leaving all the labels for the inner time series.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] If you need to keep the metric name, then add keep_metric_names modifier after the `rate(..)`.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] `rate()` must be applied only to counters .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] The result of applying the `rate()` to gauge is undefined.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] VictoriaMetrics has a built-in graphical User Interface for querying and visualizing metrics - VMUI .
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] VictoriaMetrics supports Prometheus HTTP API which makes it possible to query it with Grafana in the same way as Grafana queries Prometheus.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] VictoriaMetrics stores time series data in MergeTree -like data structures.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] While this approach is very efficient for write-heavy databases, it applies some limitations on data updates.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] In short, modifying already written time series requires re-writing the whole data block where it is stored.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Due to this limitation, VictoriaMetrics does not support direct data modification.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Relabeling is a powerful mechanism for modifying time series before they have been written to the database.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] Relabeling may be applied for both push and pull models.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] VictoriaMetrics supports data deduplication.
[src:victoriametrics/victoriametrics-keyconcepts] VictoriaMetrics supports data downsampling.
